Source file:

```csharp
using System;

public class SampleClass
{
    // This compiles with no warnings
    [Obsolete("Use NewMethod instead")]
    public void OldMethod1()
    {
        OldMethodImpl();
    }

    // This generates a warning
    [Obsolete($"Use {nameof(NewMethod)} instead")]
    public void OldMethod2()
    {
        OldMethodImpl();
    }

    // This generates a warning despite not even using
    // the fact that the string is interpolated...
    [Obsolete($"Use NewMethod instead")]
    public void OldMethod3()
    {
        OldMethodImpl();
    }

    [Obsolete("This is only called by obsolete methods")]
    private void OldMethodImpl()
    {
    }

    public void NewMethod()
    {
    }
}
```

**Expected Behavior**:

Code in methods marked as obsolete can call other obsolete methods without generating a warning, even if the message string in ObsoleteAttribute uses an interpolated string literal.

**Actual Behavior**:

The use of an interpolated string literal in ObsoleteAttribute unexpectedly changes how obsolete code within the method is handled. (Note that OldMethod1 generates no warning.)

This is particularly unfortunate as referring to "use this method instead" via nameof is one of the best uses of the C# 10 "constant interpolated strings" feature!

Consider the following code:

```c#
#nullable enable

public class Example
{
    private void Main()
    {
        // The `user` tooltip on this line shows `object?`, but it should be `object`
        var user = new object();
    }
}
```

On the line `var user = new object()`, VS shows `user` as being of type `object?`, but it should be of type `object`.

This is especially confusing when the VS setting `Display inline type hints` is enabled:

